00:02:41.260 --> 00:02:46.060
because I think you have to show
up and meet the opportunities

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:49.360
as they appear and put one
foot in front of the other

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:55.190
and think about how you can make
your talents useful to others.

00:02:55.190 --> 00:02:59.290
And this came about with
discovering that my husband was

00:02:59.290 --> 00:03:01.480
a type 2 diabetic.

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:03.370
Of course, he looks
like Omar Sharif,

00:03:03.370 --> 00:03:06.370
but that didn't mean he
didn't have diabetes.

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:09.160
And we didn't know
how to manage this

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:13.700
except with insulin shots,
which he was on for 10 years.

00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:16.390
And when I finally
retired from my business,

00:03:16.390 --> 00:03:22.010
I thought, well what happens
if I looked at food--

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:25.860
[? dinner-- ?] food as art.

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:29.030
And definitely we eat with
our eyes first, right?

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:29.710
You'd agree.

00:03:29.710 --> 00:03:32.580
If you see it and it looks
beautiful, you want to try it.

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:36.810
So I thought, is there a way
I could trick my husband--

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:38.490
like a good wife--

00:03:38.490 --> 00:03:40.740
trick him into eating healthy.

00:03:40.740 --> 00:03:45.030
Because if I told this rice
bowl kid growing up in the south

00:03:45.030 --> 00:03:46.590
of India-- rice was the staple--

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:47.340
oh, you know what?

00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:48.674
I'm just going to take rice out.

00:03:48.674 --> 00:03:49.840
I'm going to take bread out.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:51.640
I'm going to take all
the white carbs out.

00:03:51.640 --> 00:03:55.020
He's have gone shopping
for another wife.

00:03:55.020 --> 00:03:58.470
So I had to trick him into it.

00:03:58.470 --> 00:04:01.200
And the rule I apply,
for those of you

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:05.400
who like to cook and understand,
cooking in layers of flavor--

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:08.940
you can bump up the flavor if
you're taking something out.

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:12.000
So if I took out a
bad ingredient that

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.200
causes sugar spikes and weight
gain, like a refined carb,

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:19.350
I would bump it up with
an Indian gremolata

00:04:19.350 --> 00:04:22.170
or caramelized
shallots at the end.

00:04:22.170 --> 00:04:25.530
And I like to think you
can redo and recover

00:04:25.530 --> 00:04:27.780
from any mistake in cooking--

00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:32.460
and I've made my fair share
of them-- except burnt garlic.

00:04:32.460 --> 00:04:36.396
Because then you just throw
it out and start again.

00:04:36.396 --> 00:04:37.770
JAN YANEHIRO: That
was the start.

00:04:37.770 --> 00:04:38.520
DEEPA THOMAS: Yes.

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:42.540
JAN YANEHIRO: And to be honest,
in fact, with your cooking

00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:44.071
you lost 20 pounds yourself.

00:04:44.071 --> 00:04:44.820
DEEPA THOMAS: Yes.

00:04:44.820 --> 00:04:46.530
JAN YANEHIRO: Your
husband lost weight,

00:04:46.530 --> 00:04:51.320
and in fact, he is off of
insulin shots with Deepa's

00:04:51.320 --> 00:04:52.580
cooking from this book.

00:04:52.580 --> 00:04:54.660
So let that be a
lesson to all of us.

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:56.100
Now, moving on.

00:04:56.100 --> 00:05:01.440
It appears to me that Indian
cuisine is having its moment

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:03.120
here in the US.

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:04.590
It's become very popular.

00:05:04.590 --> 00:05:07.980
We're all flocking to all
the Indian restaurants.

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:10.710
Why do you think that
Indian food is now having

00:05:10.710 --> 00:05:12.617
its moment here in the US?

00:05:12.617 --> 00:05:14.200
DEEPA THOMAS: That's
a great question.

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:16.260
In fact, there was a
story in the local papers

00:05:16.260 --> 00:05:20.970
about Indian food on the
rise, and they actually

00:05:20.970 --> 00:05:22.290
asked me to say something.

00:05:22.290 --> 00:05:25.380
And I shot my mouth
off, as is my want.

00:05:25.380 --> 00:05:30.600
And what I think is happening is
borderless cuisine is probably

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:32.460
what we need to focus on.

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:36.660
Indian food has been very
much an exotic cuisine

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:38.540
for a lot of years.

00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:42.360
Now it's slowly moving
into mainstream,

00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:46.770
like before it, Italian
food did or Chinese food.

00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:49.470
I think this is the melting
pot, not just of people

00:05:49.470 --> 00:05:51.520
from different
parts of the world,

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:56.040
but of techniques and flavors.

00:05:56.040 --> 00:05:59.340
And when you can
blend the flavors

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:02.010
without creating
a flavor model--

00:06:02.010 --> 00:06:04.860
I'm not a big proponent
of fusion cuisine

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:07.600
because you don't know
what the heck it is.

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:09.720
But if you can have,
like music, clear

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:13.210
notes even if it's borrowed
from other cuisines.

00:06:13.210 --> 00:06:16.650
So Indian food is coming into
the mainstream for that reason

00:06:16.650 --> 00:06:17.910
maybe.

00:06:17.910 --> 00:06:21.420
It's always been the high
flavor ticket, right?

00:06:21.420 --> 00:06:24.284
But now people are getting
aware of its health benefits.

00:06:24.284 --> 00:06:25.200
JAN YANEHIRO: Correct.

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:29.940
And the health benefits-- do you
think it comes from the spices

00:06:29.940 --> 00:06:32.100
or how it's cooked,
the ingredients?

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:33.060
DEEPA THOMAS: Yeah.

00:06:33.060 --> 00:06:39.270
You know, it's really an irony
that India 3,000 years ago knew

00:06:39.270 --> 00:06:43.860
that food is medicine, that
when your diet is right,

00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:45.180
medicine is of no need.

00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:48.420
And when diet is wrong,
medicine is of no use.

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:51.810
This is 3,000 years
ago, Ayurveda, India.

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:55.795
Well then how can India be the
diabetic capital of the world?

00:06:55.795 --> 00:06:56.670
Isn't it interesting?

00:06:56.670 --> 00:06:57.360
JAN YANEHIRO: Yes.

00:06:57.360 --> 00:06:58.735
DEEPA THOMAS: So
what happened is

00:06:58.735 --> 00:07:01.470
what we did to ingredients
in the course of time

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:03.690
from 3,000 years to now.

00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:07.830
We treated food in
such a manner that it

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:13.380
would stay stable on supermarket
shelves and in warehouses.

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:16.900
And in the process, we overly
refined all the ingredients.

00:07:16.900 --> 00:07:19.620
So as Michael Pollan
says, eat food

00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:21.240
that your grandmother
would recognize.

00:07:21.240 --> 00:07:25.110
She wouldn't recognize
wheat today, for instance.

00:07:25.110 --> 00:07:28.770
And India knows,
but they don't know

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:32.790
how to handle modern,
industrialized ingredients.

00:07:32.790 --> 00:07:36.540
But it knows that all disease
starts in the inflammation that

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:38.190
begins in the gut.

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:40.590
And all disease--
not some disease--

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:44.010
inclusive of type 2 diabetes,
but not limited to it.

00:07:44.010 --> 00:07:48.750
So Indian ingredients from
the seeds to the spices

00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:53.190
were really a focus of the
old Ayurvedic practitioners

00:07:53.190 --> 00:07:57.760
on how to reduce inflammation
while bumping up flavor.

00:07:57.760 --> 00:07:59.250
So that's really key.

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:04.140
And what I'm trying to do is
make everything old new again.

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:08.100
It's not that I invented
this way of cooking,

00:08:08.100 --> 00:08:11.040
but I'm shining a
light on what is

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:16.740
incredibly anti-inflammatory
about Indian seeds and spices.

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:18.690
And so even if you're
cooking Italian food,

00:08:18.690 --> 00:08:20.670
throw some Indians
spices in there.

00:08:20.670 --> 00:08:22.090
JAN YANEHIRO: It's healthier.

00:08:22.090 --> 00:08:23.048
DEEPA THOMAS: Yes, yes.

00:08:23.048 --> 00:08:25.590
JAN YANEHIRO: So you talk a
lot about new Indian cuisine.

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:26.430
DEEPA THOMAS: Yes.

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:28.096
JAN YANEHIRO: Tell
the audience what you

00:08:28.096 --> 00:08:29.940
mean by the new Indian cuisine.

00:08:29.940 --> 00:08:33.789
DEEPA THOMAS: Well, I'm
an incurable brand geek.

00:08:33.789 --> 00:08:37.559
So I had to differentiate
from Indian cuisine

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:40.200
at large and new Indian cooking.

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:42.120
So what is the difference?

00:08:42.120 --> 00:08:44.190
Traditional Indian
food we all know

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:47.350
is flavorful and
exciting and exotic.

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:48.857
JAN YANEHIRO: Spicy and curried.

00:08:48.857 --> 00:08:50.940
DEEPA THOMAS: And exotic,
if you're not from India

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:52.440
I suppose.

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:56.610
But it's also high in carbs,
very high in refined carbs.

00:08:56.610 --> 00:09:00.670
It's incredibly labor intensive.

00:09:00.670 --> 00:09:03.000
So you ask what
new Indian cuisine

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:04.900
is-- it's exactly the opposite.

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:10.890
It's less labor, higher flavor,
healthier, lots of shortcuts--

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:12.630
I call them secrets--

00:09:12.630 --> 00:09:16.230
and I think that's the
positioning I'd like to take.

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:20.160
It just shines a light on
all that is potentially

00:09:20.160 --> 00:09:21.822
good about Indian cuisine.

00:09:21.822 --> 00:09:24.030
JAN YANEHIRO: And I think
that's why it's so popular.

00:09:24.030 --> 00:09:26.745
But in on your book--
here's a cover everybody--

00:09:26.745 --> 00:09:28.830
it says, "Slow Carb."

00:09:28.830 --> 00:09:30.780
You know, we hear about
this, but I'm just

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:33.570
going to ask for
everybody in the audience

00:09:33.570 --> 00:09:35.700
and across the Google campuses.

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:38.100
Tell us slow carbs--

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:40.800
what is slow carb?

00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:41.520
What is it?

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:44.790
DEEPA THOMAS: Well, we can
contrast it with low carb.

00:09:44.790 --> 00:09:49.350
Low carb cuts carb across the
board, that all carbs are bad

00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:50.790
is the approach in low carb.

00:09:50.790 --> 00:09:53.860
I don't believe that to be true.

00:09:53.860 --> 00:09:56.670
I think taking the thesis
what we do to a carb

00:09:56.670 --> 00:09:57.870
is what makes it bad.

00:09:57.870 --> 00:10:02.820
So refining it to one
inch of death is bad.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:04.920
And the whiter something is--

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:08.340
I'm sorry white people--

00:10:08.340 --> 00:10:10.340
you got to look at it again.

00:10:10.340 --> 00:10:15.690
But slow carb is closer
to the grain itself.

00:10:15.690 --> 00:10:18.960
So complex grains that
haven't been processed,

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:23.880
that make the body work to
be absorbed, higher fiber.

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:28.650
And so the longer a food
takes to be digested,

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:31.260
the better it is for you
as a simple principle.

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:33.300
The quicker it is
to be digested--

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:39.210
like sugar itself or white
carbs, potatoes, rice, flour--

00:10:39.210 --> 00:10:41.400
it converts very
quickly to sugar.

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:46.080
And all foods convert to
energy, sugar, energy.

00:10:46.080 --> 00:10:51.250
But when it's quickly
converted, it is stored as fat.

00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:54.060
So that's the big difference
between slow carb.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:58.530
You're really focusing on
low glycemic index of foods.

00:10:58.530 --> 00:11:02.409
That is how quickly or slowly
food converts to sugar.

00:11:02.409 --> 00:11:04.200
JAN YANEHIRO: So whenever
I talk to a chef,

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:07.600
I always say, well, what's
your background, your mother,

00:11:07.600 --> 00:11:10.800
your grandmother, or
some your father cook?

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:13.650
I see some people
nodding their heads.

00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:16.710
But I've read
Deepa's book, and she

00:11:16.710 --> 00:11:18.660
didn't cook as a young girl.

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:23.246
And in fact, she learned to cook
when she came here to the US.

00:11:23.246 --> 00:11:25.620
And in fact, she talks about
how she burnt her first meal

00:11:25.620 --> 00:11:26.286
for her husband.

00:11:26.286 --> 00:11:27.300
Burnt it.

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:29.280
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:31.080
JAN YANEHIRO: They
had to go get pizza.

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:33.360
But let's talk a
little bit about what

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:37.560
did you learned
growing up in India.

00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:39.990
In fact, one of your
grandparents did milk cows.

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:40.740
DEEPA THOMAS: Yes.

00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:42.480
JAN YANEHIRO: But
you didn't grow up

00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:46.660
with going into the kitchen and
learning everything and trying

00:11:46.660 --> 00:11:47.160
everything.

00:11:47.160 --> 00:11:47.989
Tell us about that.

00:11:47.989 --> 00:11:48.780
DEEPA THOMAS: Yeah.

00:11:48.780 --> 00:11:53.220
So I thought everyone grew
up with kitchen stuff, which

00:11:53.220 --> 00:11:55.050
is another thing
about Indian cooking.

00:11:55.050 --> 00:11:57.540
It's so high in labor
because it was easier

00:11:57.540 --> 00:11:59.580
to have people help
you in the kitchen.

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:03.330
Well, when I came to Stanford
campus as a young bride,

00:12:03.330 --> 00:12:06.111
I rang the bell and no one came.

00:12:06.111 --> 00:12:07.350
So good luck.

00:12:07.350 --> 00:12:09.060
Get up and do it yourself.

00:12:09.060 --> 00:12:10.740
So it was necessity.

00:12:10.740 --> 00:12:12.960
And when the kids
were growing up--

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:14.970
and Suneil will attest to this--

00:12:14.970 --> 00:12:17.700
if I got food on the table,
it was considered a win.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:19.070
It didn't matter what it was.

00:12:19.070 --> 00:12:21.960
Just food on the table.

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:27.297
But as we looked at
how we will-- you know,

00:12:27.297 --> 00:12:29.020
we were becoming successful.

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:30.450
It's the immigrant dream.

00:12:30.450 --> 00:12:33.060
Thampy and I probably
overshot the mark

00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:37.030
in all the hopes and dreams
we had to be successful.

00:12:37.030 --> 00:12:39.270
But the price we
paid was completely

00:12:39.270 --> 00:12:43.890
neglecting our own selves,
not thinking about nutrition

00:12:43.890 --> 00:12:46.830
or exercise or well-being.

00:12:46.830 --> 00:12:48.210
It was just survival.

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:49.230
You've got to make it.

00:12:49.230 --> 00:12:51.310
There's no safety net under you.

00:12:51.310 --> 00:12:52.950
So if you're in that
kind of a mindset,

00:12:52.950 --> 00:12:55.060
cooking becomes a burden.

00:12:55.060 --> 00:12:59.430
But if you start to pay
attention to the one thing you

00:12:59.430 --> 00:13:03.240
have in life,
which is your life,

00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:08.310
and you start to think about
H-O-L-E's that never get filled

00:13:08.310 --> 00:13:11.862
with food, I think it took me--

00:13:11.862 --> 00:13:14.320
I'm a very slow learner, as
you've probably guessed by now,

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:18.700
but it took me the better
part of half a century

00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:20.350
to really get there.

00:13:20.350 --> 00:13:23.540
So I had a very adversarial
relationship with food.

00:13:23.540 --> 00:13:26.040
And I don't know how many
people in this room would relate

00:13:26.040 --> 00:13:28.240
or across the campuses.

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:31.050
But the fact is food,
if you're a woman--

00:13:31.050 --> 00:13:33.700
at least, it was in my culture--

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:34.570
oh, don't eat it.

00:13:34.570 --> 00:13:36.010
You'll get fat.

00:13:36.010 --> 00:13:36.949
Right?

00:13:36.949 --> 00:13:38.240
JAN YANEHIRO: This culture too.

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:38.620
DEEPA THOMAS: Yeah.

00:13:38.620 --> 00:13:39.610
Or I'm depressed.

00:13:39.610 --> 00:13:41.530
I'm just going to
have a bag of chips.

00:13:41.530 --> 00:13:43.660
Well, both ends don't work.

00:13:43.660 --> 00:13:48.270
And I talk about my own journey
with the H-O-L-E's that never

00:13:48.270 --> 00:13:50.020
get filled with food.

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:55.330
And then so you look at
food as your nourishment

00:13:55.330 --> 00:14:00.299
for your spirit and body,
but not just for your body.

00:14:00.299 --> 00:14:02.590
JAN YANEHIRO: And we've been
talking about her husband.

00:14:02.590 --> 00:14:04.390
And Thampy is here.

00:14:04.390 --> 00:14:08.290
And in fact, it was sort
of an arranged marriage.

00:14:08.290 --> 00:14:08.945
Sort of.

00:14:08.945 --> 00:14:09.736
DEEPA THOMAS: Yeah.

00:14:09.736 --> 00:14:12.490
JAN YANEHIRO: But he was
considered the most eligible

00:14:12.490 --> 00:14:16.180
bachelor back in her home state.

00:14:16.180 --> 00:14:19.040
And he was studying
here at Stanford.

00:14:19.040 --> 00:14:21.712
And she thought, oh well.

00:14:21.712 --> 00:14:23.920
I mean, her family said,
oh, you've got to marry him.

00:14:23.920 --> 00:14:25.600
And you didn't quite
have that idea.

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:26.308
DEEPA THOMAS: No.

00:14:26.308 --> 00:14:29.350
JAN YANEHIRO: And I say
this because she has helped

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:32.080
have him get his health back.

00:14:32.080 --> 00:14:34.000
They have two
children, two sons.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:35.710
And her son is here.

00:14:35.710 --> 00:14:37.990
He's one of the reasons why
we are all here because he

00:14:37.990 --> 00:14:38.980
works here at Google.

00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:40.050
DEEPA THOMAS: Uh-huh.

00:14:40.050 --> 00:14:41.590
Suneil Thomas.

00:14:41.590 --> 00:14:44.360
JAN YANEHIRO: So you know, this
is a family affair right here.

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:47.170
So I just want to digress
just a little bit about this

00:14:47.170 --> 00:14:48.590
and then just say--

00:14:48.590 --> 00:14:50.170
this is a reporter question.

00:14:50.170 --> 00:14:52.650
Both you and your
husband are immigrants.

00:14:52.650 --> 00:14:55.430
So this is slightly
off topic from food,

00:14:55.430 --> 00:14:57.660
but you both are immigrants.

00:14:57.660 --> 00:15:01.750
You both became huge successes
here, raised your family here,

00:15:01.750 --> 00:15:03.220
your children.

00:15:03.220 --> 00:15:06.850
What do you feel about the
immigrants in America today

00:15:06.850 --> 00:15:08.050
and what should happen?

00:15:08.050 --> 00:15:09.440
So this is a political question.

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:10.090
Forgive me.

00:15:10.090 --> 00:15:10.828
I'm a reporter.

00:15:10.828 --> 00:15:12.286
DEEPA THOMAS: She's
going off book.

00:15:12.286 --> 00:15:14.619
JAN YANEHIRO: Off book, but
we'll come back to the book.

00:15:14.619 --> 00:15:15.850
So what do you think?

00:15:15.850 --> 00:15:19.810
Well, you know, one has to
look at a personal journey,

00:15:19.810 --> 00:15:22.060
and times have changed.

00:15:22.060 --> 00:15:25.360
When Thampy and I
came here, I think

00:15:25.360 --> 00:15:27.330
Suneil will attest to this--

00:15:27.330 --> 00:15:30.730
by the time we had Suneil,
he was the first Indian

00:15:30.730 --> 00:15:35.170
in all of the Portola Valley
schools, which is unbelievable.

00:15:35.170 --> 00:15:36.340
You see him sitting there.

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:37.650
He's not that old.

00:15:37.650 --> 00:15:40.340
He is rudely very old.

00:15:40.340 --> 00:15:42.040
So things have changed.

00:15:42.040 --> 00:15:48.940
And the understanding
of ethnic difference--

00:15:48.940 --> 00:15:54.490
what has happened to the
American economy and how the 1%

00:15:54.490 --> 00:15:56.050
is literally--

00:15:56.050 --> 00:15:58.120
and we probably are in the 1%.

00:15:58.120 --> 00:16:02.200
So I can say this today--
when we came here, Thampy

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:07.240
was making $300 a month
assistantship at Stanford

00:16:07.240 --> 00:16:09.610
doing his PhD.

00:16:09.610 --> 00:16:11.320
Try living on $300.

00:16:11.320 --> 00:16:14.340
Well, I spent $50
on a straw hat.

00:16:14.340 --> 00:16:17.100
So that took care
of the first month.

00:16:17.100 --> 00:16:18.760
You know, we had to learn.

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:19.810
But here we are.

00:16:19.810 --> 00:16:23.960
The minute we became
successful, you

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:27.680
have this need to hold
that door open for others.

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:31.130
So I don't know when you
want to talk about this, Jan,

00:16:31.130 --> 00:16:34.010
I think I'd like to
talk through FoodCorps,

00:16:34.010 --> 00:16:36.230
the reason I got involved.

00:16:36.230 --> 00:16:39.680
This entire book and
all of my royalty

00:16:39.680 --> 00:16:42.450
will go to a nonprofit
called FoodCorps.

00:16:42.450 --> 00:16:43.700
And why?

00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:47.720
Because my American
friends who grew up

00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:49.670
being told to finish
what's on their plate

00:16:49.670 --> 00:16:52.370
because there are
kids starving in India

00:16:52.370 --> 00:16:54.530
fall off their chairs
when I tell them

00:16:54.530 --> 00:16:59.330
that one out of five
kids in American schools

00:16:59.330 --> 00:17:02.350
is going to bed hungry
and waking up hungry.

00:17:02.350 --> 00:17:03.860
It is just not OK.

00:17:03.860 --> 00:17:05.690
It's not a political thing.

00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:07.700
So when I met Kurt Ellis--

00:17:07.700 --> 00:17:09.920
that's a longer story-- but
he's written the forward

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:11.569
to my book--

00:17:11.569 --> 00:17:15.500
he is the founding
CEO of FoodCorps--

00:17:15.500 --> 00:17:17.690
I found a new hero.

00:17:17.690 --> 00:17:20.240
This young man came
out of Yale and figured

00:17:20.240 --> 00:17:25.849
out how to create a
scalable nonprofit which

00:17:25.849 --> 00:17:29.250
goes into the schools and
works with the schools,

00:17:29.250 --> 00:17:31.450
especially in
underprivileged areas,

00:17:31.450 --> 00:17:34.730
to do something about
the lunch programs

00:17:34.730 --> 00:17:39.240
and connect the kids
to healthy food habits.

00:17:39.240 --> 00:17:44.510
So I think the immigrant story
is one of desperately trying

00:17:44.510 --> 00:17:49.580
to succeed, and then some
of us are fortunate enough

00:17:49.580 --> 00:17:52.490
to make it and ask the
question, how much is enough?

00:17:52.490 --> 00:17:53.270
How much money?

00:17:53.270 --> 00:17:54.840
How much food?

00:17:54.840 --> 00:17:57.230
And when you answer
that question,

00:17:57.230 --> 00:18:00.090
you hold the door
open for others.

00:18:00.090 --> 00:18:02.540
And if you want to get into
all the politics of today,

00:18:02.540 --> 00:18:05.480
I think it's ridiculous.

00:18:05.480 --> 00:18:08.870
But the fact is we're individual
human beings all aspiring to be

00:18:08.870 --> 00:18:12.920
successful, and I'd like
to stay with that thought

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:16.050
of philanthropy and immigrants.

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:19.280
It's a new story, I think,
because philanthropy was always

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:20.810
part of the American history.

00:18:20.810 --> 00:18:24.440
But for immigrants,
it's sort of a luxury

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:26.840
to even think about
it, and we might

00:18:26.840 --> 00:18:28.970
be on the first wave of it.

00:18:28.970 --> 00:18:30.930
So I'm proud of that.

00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:32.150
JAN YANEHIRO: And we are too.

00:18:32.150 --> 00:18:36.860
So the proceeds from this
book will go to FoodCorps.

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:38.250
DEEPA THOMAS: My royalties.

00:18:38.250 --> 00:18:39.150
JAN YANEHIRO: Deepa's royalties.

00:18:39.150 --> 00:18:40.940
And for that, I think
we need to-- yeah.

00:18:40.940 --> 00:18:43.850
[APPLAUSE]

00:18:43.850 --> 00:18:46.640
JAN YANEHIRO: So I do
want to open up for Q&amp;A

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:48.710
and leave you a lot
of time for that.

00:18:48.710 --> 00:18:52.070
And we've got Chef
Dina here and her team.

00:18:52.070 --> 00:18:54.440
So I'm going to
say, Dina, you're

00:18:54.440 --> 00:18:56.520
first up for the questions.

00:18:56.520 --> 00:19:00.140
So let's give Dina a microphone.

00:19:00.140 --> 00:19:02.440
And we want to ask everybody
else to chime in too.

00:19:02.440 --> 00:19:05.149
So Dina, thank you for
preparing today's menu.

00:19:05.149 --> 00:19:07.190
CHEF DINA: Oh, it was my
pleasure, but thank you.

00:19:07.190 --> 00:19:09.148
JAN YANEHIRO: What would
you like to ask Deepa?

00:19:09.148 --> 00:19:11.420
JAN YANEHIRO: I wondering
what really brought you

00:19:11.420 --> 00:19:13.302
into the idea of
writing this book?

00:19:13.302 --> 00:19:15.260
What was your inspiration
for really spreading?

00:19:15.260 --> 00:19:17.260
DEEPA THOMAS: That's a
very good question, Dina.

00:19:17.260 --> 00:19:18.260
It took five years.

00:19:18.260 --> 00:19:19.260
And I tried to say, no.

00:19:19.260 --> 00:19:19.760
No.

00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:20.259
No.

00:19:20.259 --> 00:19:21.130
It's not me.

00:19:21.130 --> 00:19:22.670
And this is not
what I want to do.

00:19:22.670 --> 00:19:26.240
And to the first order, I
wanted to document my recipes

00:19:26.240 --> 00:19:29.670
for my sons because both
of them like to cook.

00:19:29.670 --> 00:19:34.400
And it was really a dear friend
of mine who is Susan Dreyfus,

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:36.860
and she's in this
book as a chapter.

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:43.105
Susan is an award winning Oscar
nominated documentary filmmaker

00:19:43.105 --> 00:19:44.160
it turns out.

00:19:44.160 --> 00:19:47.060
But that aside, she and I served
on the Board of Rhode Island

00:19:47.060 --> 00:19:50.310
School of Design together,
and we became good friends.

00:19:50.310 --> 00:19:53.300
And it was Susan,
who in her kitchen--

00:19:53.300 --> 00:19:56.810
and she hates to cook, but she
had a really beautiful kitchen

00:19:56.810 --> 00:19:58.130
in New York--

00:19:58.130 --> 00:20:01.070
she turned an
imaginary lens onto me

00:20:01.070 --> 00:20:05.240
and said, what was your
first memory with food?

00:20:05.240 --> 00:20:07.970
And out came tumbling my
story of my grandmother

00:20:07.970 --> 00:20:10.699
who's in this book.

00:20:10.699 --> 00:20:11.990
And she said, freeze the frame.

00:20:11.990 --> 00:20:13.340
I said, I beg your pardon.

00:20:13.340 --> 00:20:16.470
And she said, write it
the way you said it.

00:20:16.470 --> 00:20:20.390
Because if you connect
your life stories

00:20:20.390 --> 00:20:25.220
and how improbable it was that
you would write a cookbook--

00:20:25.220 --> 00:20:28.640
but if you write those stories,
maybe the people who read it

00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:31.580
will not be intimidated
by the recipes

00:20:31.580 --> 00:20:32.970
that, yes, I've simplified it.

00:20:32.970 --> 00:20:35.120
I've have taken the
labor out of it.

00:20:35.120 --> 00:20:38.090
I've tried to Americanize
the understanding

00:20:38.090 --> 00:20:42.050
of the ingredients and process.

00:20:42.050 --> 00:20:46.480
But the real impetus was what--

00:20:46.480 --> 00:20:51.980
it was so shocking that
five days of an accidental

00:20:51.980 --> 00:20:54.380
turn in Thampy's life,
my husband's life,

00:20:54.380 --> 00:20:57.500
where he forgot to take
his insulin shot, which

00:20:57.500 --> 00:21:01.010
was grounds for panic in our
household back in the day.

00:21:01.010 --> 00:21:03.500
But when he took his blood
sugar after five days

00:21:03.500 --> 00:21:06.690
of eating this way, his
blood sugar was normal.

00:21:06.690 --> 00:21:08.570
So we-- our last
name is Thomas--

00:21:08.570 --> 00:21:11.820
so Doubting Thomases
ran off to Walgreens

00:21:11.820 --> 00:21:15.890
and got another monitor,
and it remained normal.

00:21:15.890 --> 00:21:18.380
So then I told my
general physician

00:21:18.380 --> 00:21:21.170
who is the associate
dean of UCSF,

00:21:21.170 --> 00:21:22.670
and he said, Mrs.
Thomas, you better

00:21:22.670 --> 00:21:24.970
come in tell us
what you're doing

00:21:24.970 --> 00:21:29.020
because there are three million
Indians in America alone

00:21:29.020 --> 00:21:31.519
and 50% are diabetic.

00:21:31.519 --> 00:21:33.310
India is the diabetic
capital of the world.

00:21:33.310 --> 00:21:36.550
One third of the adult
population of America

00:21:36.550 --> 00:21:40.150
is fighting obesity
or diabetes or both.

00:21:40.150 --> 00:21:41.500
It's related.

00:21:41.500 --> 00:21:45.820
So I felt if I was
going to do this then

00:21:45.820 --> 00:21:48.640
this is going to be my gift.

00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:51.730
And now our other
son, he and his wife

00:21:51.730 --> 00:21:53.770
had our first grandchild.

00:21:53.770 --> 00:21:58.720
And so of course it is
a gift to her, I hope,

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:03.220
that to write the course--

00:22:03.220 --> 00:22:07.160
you know, there's been so
many challenges in life.

00:22:07.160 --> 00:22:08.290
We all have them.

00:22:08.290 --> 00:22:10.880
But how we overcome them.

00:22:10.880 --> 00:22:13.330
And did I think I'd
write a cookbook?

00:22:13.330 --> 00:22:14.110
No.

00:22:14.110 --> 00:22:18.220
But that it sold 10,000
copies in three months,

00:22:18.220 --> 00:22:20.119
they tell me is something good.

00:22:20.119 --> 00:22:21.160
JAN YANEHIRO: It is good.

00:22:21.160 --> 00:22:22.680
It's fabulous.

00:22:22.680 --> 00:22:23.680
DEEPA THOMAS: Thank you.

00:22:23.680 --> 00:22:26.350
JAN YANEHIRO: And we want to
say that Thampy, her husband,

00:22:26.350 --> 00:22:27.455
is still off of insulin.

00:22:27.455 --> 00:22:28.300
DEEPA THOMAS: Yes.

00:22:28.300 --> 00:22:29.309
Six years and counting.

00:22:29.309 --> 00:22:30.850
JAN YANEHIRO: Six
years and counting.

00:22:30.850 --> 00:22:34.240
And ever since he started to--

00:22:34.240 --> 00:22:36.790
because Deepa has
secrets in this book.

00:22:36.790 --> 00:22:41.860
So ladies, you're
part of the crew here

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:45.400
that prepare healthy foods
for all the Google employees.

00:22:45.400 --> 00:22:46.330
Questions from you.

