00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:31.450
suggestions of how to
bring up well-being.

00:24:31.450 --> 00:24:36.230
And this was my approach
to the whole of this book,

00:24:36.230 --> 00:24:41.350
and Indian food
suffers sometimes

00:24:41.350 --> 00:24:43.840
from lack of thoughtfulness.

00:24:43.840 --> 00:24:47.350
The flavor is overwhelmingly
either beautiful or spicy,

00:24:47.350 --> 00:24:48.160
and you eat it.

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:49.360
And that's it.

00:24:49.360 --> 00:24:53.440
But to take the time to
present an ancient cuisine that

00:24:53.440 --> 00:24:56.140
has health benefits
and is beautiful.

00:24:56.140 --> 00:24:57.310
I mean, this was--

00:24:57.310 --> 00:25:00.670
when Sherry Heck, the
photographer in my kitchen,

00:25:00.670 --> 00:25:03.610
saw what I was putting out
for one of the recipes,

00:25:03.610 --> 00:25:04.540
she said, stop.

00:25:04.540 --> 00:25:06.100
Let me take a picture of that.

00:25:06.100 --> 00:25:08.880
So this was that shot.

00:25:08.880 --> 00:25:12.930
I put this nutmeg with
the mace around it,

00:25:12.930 --> 00:25:18.460
is from my husband's younger
brother's backyard in Kerala.

00:25:18.460 --> 00:25:21.850
So I had just thrown it
on the cutting board,

00:25:21.850 --> 00:25:22.900
and we took a shot of it.

00:25:22.900 --> 00:25:24.460
It's that beautiful.

00:25:24.460 --> 00:25:25.960
So why wouldn't
we lead with that?

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:26.320
JAN YANEHIRO: Right.

00:25:26.320 --> 00:25:27.480
So it is beautiful.

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:30.670
Maybe you can talk about some
of the other spices on the book.

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:32.477
So the nutmeg.

00:25:32.477 --> 00:25:33.310
And then we've got--

00:25:33.310 --> 00:25:35.980
DEEPA THOMAS: Well, if you
start from the center out,

00:25:35.980 --> 00:25:38.380
most of the spice
wars were fought

00:25:38.380 --> 00:25:41.221
over this little
creature called a cloves.

00:25:41.221 --> 00:25:42.220
JAN YANEHIRO: Which is--

00:25:42.220 --> 00:25:43.636
DEEPA THOMAS: Right
in the middle,

00:25:43.636 --> 00:25:46.280
and it's that
long-ish right there.

00:25:46.280 --> 00:25:46.780
Right there.

00:25:46.780 --> 00:25:47.560
JAN YANEHIRO: OK.

00:25:47.560 --> 00:25:49.226
DEEPA THOMAS: And
then this is cardamom.

00:25:49.226 --> 00:25:51.640
So clove and
cardamon and cinnamon

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:54.970
were the lead reasons why
trading with the South of India

00:25:54.970 --> 00:25:58.750
was so through all the ages.

00:25:58.750 --> 00:26:03.210
And we feel that even
during the biblical times,

00:26:03.210 --> 00:26:05.630
St. Thomas came to
the south of India--

00:26:05.630 --> 00:26:07.990
our church that we
belong to, Thampy and I,

00:26:07.990 --> 00:26:13.000
dates back to St. Thomas was
martyred in Kerala apparently.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:15.310
So you go on with--

00:26:15.310 --> 00:26:19.180
I'd like to talk about this
actual spice in the background.

00:26:19.180 --> 00:26:22.450
We think curry powder is
an Indian spice blend.

00:26:22.450 --> 00:26:24.240
It is not.

00:26:24.240 --> 00:26:30.180
It is a signature blend that
every housewife would make up

00:26:30.180 --> 00:26:34.740
in her kitchen, and every mix
would be slightly different.

00:26:34.740 --> 00:26:37.590
And then the Brits
happened in India.

00:26:37.590 --> 00:26:40.350
And so they created
this thing called

00:26:40.350 --> 00:26:43.230
curry powder, which can
be quite nauseating I

00:26:43.230 --> 00:26:44.896
find in the stores.

00:26:44.896 --> 00:26:46.020
And that's the other thing.

00:26:46.020 --> 00:26:47.730
If you have spices
in your kitchen

00:26:47.730 --> 00:26:52.530
that have been there for more
than six months, throw it out.

00:26:52.530 --> 00:26:54.690
I had stuff when we
moved from years,

00:26:54.690 --> 00:26:56.370
and I thought, oh my god.

00:26:56.370 --> 00:26:58.200
So all the nutritional
value is gone.

00:26:58.200 --> 00:27:01.140
It smells and
tastes like sawdust.

00:27:01.140 --> 00:27:04.540
It is important to
keep whole spices.

00:27:04.540 --> 00:27:07.650
So that spice there is powdered.

00:27:07.650 --> 00:27:09.540
And of course, it
includes turmeric,

00:27:09.540 --> 00:27:11.760
which gives that the yellow.

00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:16.770
But it would have coriander
seeds, cumin seeds, anise seed,

00:27:16.770 --> 00:27:18.170
fennel seed.

00:27:18.170 --> 00:27:21.060
And if you kept seeds in your
kitchen, you can toast them up

00:27:21.060 --> 00:27:23.370
and grind them and
that is much better way

00:27:23.370 --> 00:27:26.550
to go than have ground spices.

00:27:26.550 --> 00:27:31.490
And I give you recipes for
my curry blend and also

00:27:31.490 --> 00:27:33.690
Deepa's secret spice,
which someday I

00:27:33.690 --> 00:27:37.560
hope to productize because
then I can help more kids.

00:27:37.560 --> 00:27:42.150
But it's 16 different spices
toasted and ground up,

00:27:42.150 --> 00:27:46.620
and a pinch of it will make
your omelet taste one way.

00:27:46.620 --> 00:27:51.540
And three tablespoons of it will
take your roast another way.

00:27:51.540 --> 00:27:53.320
The recipe's in
the book as well.

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:55.320
JAN YANEHIRO: So does
that answer your question?

00:27:55.320 --> 00:27:55.820
Yes.

00:27:55.820 --> 00:27:57.850
And do you have
another question here?

00:27:57.850 --> 00:28:00.930
You also work in
food service here.

00:28:00.930 --> 00:28:02.100
So tell us your question.

