And she actually learned
to cook here in USA.

00:30:10.380 --> 00:30:12.952
So there's a lead.

00:30:12.952 --> 00:30:13.910
DEEPA THOMAS: There is.

00:30:13.910 --> 00:30:18.000
And I think your question
is how do I view it now

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:21.120
that I'm more conscious
about how I shop,

00:30:21.120 --> 00:30:23.940
what I keep in the fridge,
what I have in my pantry,

00:30:23.940 --> 00:30:26.330
and there's a whole
chapter dedicated to that.

00:30:26.330 --> 00:30:31.190
From my own knowledge of
if you come home tired,

00:30:31.190 --> 00:30:33.570
I can't imagine you guys
going home and deciding

00:30:33.570 --> 00:30:36.180
to cook for yourself.

00:30:36.180 --> 00:30:38.760
It was a big challenge for
me when the kids were young

00:30:38.760 --> 00:30:40.770
and I was running
my own business.

00:30:40.770 --> 00:30:45.060
Now therefore, I've given
a cheat list of things

00:30:45.060 --> 00:30:47.980
to keep on hand so you
can whip up a meal,

00:30:47.980 --> 00:30:50.220
even if you don't
go grocery shopping.

00:30:50.220 --> 00:30:53.160
So that's the first thing, to
get a little bit organized.

00:30:53.160 --> 00:30:57.360
And I love and I'm obsessed
with farmer's markets.

00:30:57.360 --> 00:30:59.172
So whenever I get a
chance on a Saturday

00:30:59.172 --> 00:31:00.630
go down to the
[INAUDIBLE] building

00:31:00.630 --> 00:31:05.350
and elbow out the chefs
who are also shopping.

00:31:05.350 --> 00:31:07.230
JAN YANEHIRO: Dina, maybe you.

00:31:07.230 --> 00:31:10.470
DEEPA THOMAS: And so living
in California, we have access

00:31:10.470 --> 00:31:14.440
