by the complexities
of Indian food,

00:34:03.030 --> 00:34:06.690
who doesn't have
much time, who is--

00:34:06.690 --> 00:34:08.580
I'm a little older than
the millennial age--

00:34:08.580 --> 00:34:15.719
but at the same time want to
prepare dishes, meals quickly?

00:34:15.719 --> 00:34:17.489
And where would you start?

00:34:17.489 --> 00:34:19.530
How would you approach
it if you've never

00:34:19.530 --> 00:34:20.760
cooked Indian food?

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:22.980
DEEPA THOMAS: Oh, that's
a terrific question.

00:34:22.980 --> 00:34:27.630
And then this is spot on
because I was that person.

00:34:27.630 --> 00:34:28.840
I didn't know how to cook.

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:31.139
I scorched my first meal.

00:34:31.139 --> 00:34:35.550
And there weren't great teachers
who could have taught me.

00:34:35.550 --> 00:34:37.770
What I remembered of my
grandmother and mother's

00:34:37.770 --> 00:34:39.960
cooking informed me.

00:34:39.960 --> 00:34:43.650
And I think I'd say,
approach Indian food--

00:34:43.650 --> 00:34:45.437
now, do you cook generally?

00:34:45.437 --> 00:34:46.020
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:34:46.020 --> 00:34:46.978
DEEPA THOMAS: Fabulous.

00:34:46.978 --> 00:34:48.120
Start there.

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:50.820
Approach it with
the comfort you have

00:34:50.820 --> 00:34:53.639
cooking the foods you know
how to cook because that's how

00:34:53.639 --> 00:34:55.889
I approached Indian cuisine.

00:34:55.889 --> 00:34:58.860
I brought in the techniques
from other cuisines

00:34:58.860 --> 00:35:00.900
that I was familiar with.

00:35:00.900 --> 00:35:05.550
And you can open up the
earlier pages of the book

00:35:05.550 --> 00:35:06.820
and look at the recipes.

00:35:06.820 --> 00:35:09.390
They're really the ABC's.

00:35:09.390 --> 00:35:12.810
I recommend very
strongly, especially

00:35:12.810 --> 00:35:15.150
with the focus of type 2
diabetes and just losing

00:35:15.150 --> 00:35:18.420
weight and being healthy,
a protein breakfast.

00:35:18.420 --> 00:35:22.830
So I say, for instance, a stir
fry or a grilled vegetable

00:35:22.830 --> 00:35:27.270
from the previous night
and I break an egg open

00:35:27.270 --> 00:35:30.997
in a pan with onions under
it so it caramelizes it

00:35:30.997 --> 00:35:32.580
as it's cooking and
then put it on top

00:35:32.580 --> 00:35:34.770
of the stirred vegetables.

00:35:34.770 --> 00:35:37.200
That's Indian food also.

00:35:37.200 --> 00:35:40.860
So now if you want to get into
a little more complicated stuff

00:35:40.860 --> 00:35:43.050
I've got, for
instance, I think one

00:35:43.050 --> 00:35:46.890
of Suneil's favorite things,
the new Indian cacciatore,

00:35:46.890 --> 00:35:49.110
the chicken dish,
which is really

00:35:49.110 --> 00:35:51.840
reminiscent of the
Italian technique.

00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:56.040
But there's just enough
Indian flavor and twist

00:35:56.040 --> 00:35:57.810
to keep it familiar.

00:35:57.810 --> 00:36:00.220
So pick the recipes,
I would say.

00:36:00.220 --> 00:36:02.610
And if you're not going to
have this book, approach

00:36:02.610 --> 00:36:07.870
Indian food from your comfort
level, not what you don't know.

00:36:07.870 --> 00:36:09.120
I mean, throw in some spice.

00:36:09.120 --> 00:36:11.070
How bad can it be?

00:36:11.070 --> 00:36:15.090
Toasting cumin seeds-- if
there's one thing people

00:36:15.090 --> 00:36:16.030
will try.

00:36:16.030 --> 00:36:19.680
Toast the cumin seeds until
it's got this nutty flavor

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:22.920
and short of going
black and burnt.

00:36:22.920 --> 00:36:26.760
So really a good
cinnamon char on it.

00:36:26.760 --> 00:36:31.170
And then when it's cool, powder
it and sprinkle it on stuff.

00:36:31.170 --> 00:36:33.870
I mean, make up your
own Indian recipes.

00:36:33.870 --> 00:36:35.730
I want to encourage
people to go off

00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:40.380
because I learned exactly the
way you're asking the question.

00:36:40.380 --> 00:36:41.290
What is Indian food?

00:36:41.290 --> 00:36:41.790
Oh, my god.

